item.description:
 &ldquo;If something can be done in two minutes, do it immediately&rdquo;
The idea is to get the momentum going and getting those quick and easy things done as soon as possible. Every time we finish a task, the brain will create a dose of dopamine making us feel better, and that will in turn make our brain create a craving for another dose of dopamine.
Sources # How the 2-minute rule can help you beat procrastination and start new habits Related 5-second-rule 5-minute-rule

&ldquo;Promise yourself to do only 5 minutes of work on a task you&rsquo;re putting off&rdquo;
Sometimes, it can be really hard to get started because the task we&rsquo;re going to do just feels overwhelmingly large or complex. Try to break the task down to the smallest possible sub-task (convert it into an Input Based Goal) and give yourself 5 minutes to work on it.
Example: if your goal is to get to the gym, promise yourself that you&rsquo;ll only spend 5 minutes packing your gym-bag.

 &ldquo;More probable behaviours will reinforce less probable behaviours.&rdquo;
You become conditioned to do something you don&rsquo;t want to do, because you get to do something else that you want to do when you do the less desirable action.
Sources How to become 37.78 times better at anything | Atomic Habits summary (by James Clear) Related Atomic Habits
